    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_3899509066" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3899509066" />
    <a title="JimZ" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/99765491-jimz"><img alt="JimZ" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1575257175p2/99765491.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3899509066?book_show_action=true">Mar 20, 2021</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="JimZ" class="user" itemprop="url" name="JimZ" href="/user/show/99765491-jimz">JimZ</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3899509066" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer12920376160182388922">I read Helen Macdonald’s Vesper Flights in late 2020 and liked it...there were 41 essays and some shone and others not so brightly but the ones that shone certainly made up for things. And I certainly grew to respect this author for her intelligence and her writing. <br/><br/>I liked her later work more than this work, which as of today (March 20, 2021) has received 63,085 ratings and 8,466 reviews. Good God! 😮<br/><br/>Refreshing to see those number of reviews for a memoir/nature/animal behavior work of literature</span>
  <span id="freeText12920376160182388922" style="display:none">I read Helen Macdonald’s Vesper Flights in late 2020 and liked it...there were 41 essays and some shone and others not so brightly but the ones that shone certainly made up for things. And I certainly grew to respect this author for her intelligence and her writing. <br /><br />I liked her later work more than this work, which as of today (March 20, 2021) has received 63,085 ratings and 8,466 reviews. Good God! 😮<br /><br />Refreshing to see those number of reviews for a memoir/nature/animal behavior work of literature.<br /><br />I would have liked this book more had Helen Macdonald early on had talked about the ethics of falconry and the reasons for its existence in the 20th and 21st century. I was having a hard time accepting its practice. I was finally so bugged by this—that I knew there was apparently widespread acceptance of falconry today in the 21st century (so why shouldn’t I accept it)?—that I went to Wikipedia (<a target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow" href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Falconry">https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Falconry</a> ) and read about hawking from somebody other than Helen Macdonald and then went to watch two videos on YouTube, and then I “got it”. I accepted it, and then I could go back to the book (I had about 9 chapters to go) without that doubt/cognitive dissonance in the back of my mind. All I needed was a damn explanation for why she did what she did...if that had come earlier in the book, I think I would have appreciated it more.<br /><br />Another element that I did not like a whole lot about the book—and it was a deliberate focus of the book—was her telling us of T. H. White and his attempts at hawking. It seemed that at times every other chapter was about him, and I just thought there was too much of him in there. I did not find him to be super-interesting, and I didn’t care all that much about him, and she kept on going back to him. Again, I am probably in the minority because his book/diary of training a hawk is considered by some to be a wonderful book (Goshawk).<br /><br />The other thing I did not like was that, to my mind, Helen Macdonald was a not a very likable character as she portrayed herself in the memoir. I understood she was grieving for her father, and so the relationship she had with him and how she reacted to his death should be something I fully accept and respect. Still, she did not seem all that friendly to people around her, and she often wanted them to go away so she could be with her hawk, etc. etc. But then I realized as she disclosed late in the book that she was suffering from a deep clinical depression. And then it all made sense to me. And by book’s end, she was coming out of her depression, and I was very glad for her.<br /><br />So basically, it was my misunderstanding of things that made me dislike it for a good chunk of time that I was reading it. Once I understood things, then my overall feeling to the book was a positive one. If that makes any sense. 🤨<br /><br />Reviews:<br />•	<a target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow" href="https://www.nytimes.com/2015/02/22/books/review/helen-macdonalds-h-is-for-hawk.html">https://www.nytimes.com/2015/02/22/bo...</a> <br />•	<a target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow" href="https://www.theguardian.com/books/2014/jul/23/h-is-for-hawk-helen-macdonald-review">https://www.theguardian.com/books/201...</a> <br />•	wow, I guess I’m not the only one with problems with this book… <a target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow" href="https://www.irishtimes.com/culture/books/bird-tale-that-fails-to-fly-h-is-for-hawk-by-helen-macdonald-1.1917840">https://www.irishtimes.com/culture/bo...</a></span>
  <a data-text-id="12920376160182388922" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

