  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_2094317047" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2094317047" />
    <a title="Chrissie" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/632247-chrissie"><img alt="Chrissie" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1321799585p2/632247.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2094317047?book_show_action=true">Aug 16, 2017</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Chrissie" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Chrissie" href="/user/show/632247-chrissie">Chrissie</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was ok"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was ok</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/632247-chrissie?shelf=bio">bio</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/632247-chrissie?shelf=england">england</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/632247-chrissie?shelf=flora">flora</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/632247-chrissie?shelf=returned">returned</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/632247-chrissie?shelf=2017-read">2017-read</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/632247-chrissie?shelf=audible">audible</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/632247-chrissie?shelf=fauna">fauna</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/632247-chrissie?shelf=arts">arts</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/632247-chrissie?shelf=philo-psychol">philo-psychol</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/632247-chrissie?shelf=lgtb">lgtb</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2094317047" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer9286997174884935367">Why only two stars? The simple answer is that the book was only OK for me. <br/><br/>The book is said to be about how the author, at the death of her father, dealt with her grief. She was thirty-seven when he died, he sixty-seven. All of her life she had been fascinated by raptors, had read about them and trained them. To cope with her grief, she determined she would train a goshawk. How could training a raptor help her handle her grief and subsequent depression? This was my question. On completing the bo</span>
  <span id="freeText9286997174884935367" style="display:none">Why only two stars? The simple answer is that the book was only OK for me. <br /><br />The book is said to be about how the author, at the death of her father, dealt with her grief. She was thirty-seven when he died, he sixty-seven. All of her life she had been fascinated by raptors, had read about them and trained them. To cope with her grief, she determined she would train a goshawk. How could training a raptor help her handle her grief and subsequent depression? This was my question. On completing the book, I am not sure I have an adequate answer! The next question is easier. Why did she choose a goshawk? Training such a bird would be a challenge and she had <b>always</b> been interested in them. They “resemble sparrow hawks the way leopards resemble house cats.” Bigger, bulkier, bloodier, deadlier. From her childhood, she had been drawn to falconry and specifically to the writings of naturalist and author <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/author/show/426944.T_H__White" title="T.H. White" rel="nofollow noopener">T.H. White</a>. He is the author of <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/1188127.The_Goshawk" title="The Goshawk by T.H. White" rel="nofollow noopener">The Goshawk</a> and renowned for his series <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/43545.The_Once_and_Future_King__The_Once_and_Future_King__1_4_" title="The Once and Future King (The Once and Future King #1-4) by T.H. White" rel="nofollow noopener">The Once and Future King</a>, beginning with <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/316845.The_Sword_in_the_Stone__The_Once_and_Future_King___1_" title="The Sword in the Stone (The Once and Future King, #1) by T.H. White" rel="nofollow noopener">The Sword in the Stone</a> and concluding with <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/48044.The_Book_of_Merlyn__The_Once_and_Future_King___5_" title="The Book of Merlyn (The Once and Future King, #5) by T.H. White" rel="nofollow noopener">The Book of Merlyn</a>. Note that <u>Helen Macdonald's book is as much about T.H. White as it is about the author's months training her goshawk, Mabel.</u> His story centers around themes of being a pawn of his parents, not belonging, homosexuality and of course falconry. Fans of White ‘s books may find Macdonald’s book more interesting than I did. There is more biographical information on White than there is about Macdonald or her dead, beloved father!<br /><br />The telling flits back and forth between chapters on falconry, Helen's childhood and T.H. White. I found the reading disjointed; flipping between subjects was disconcerting. The shifts are abrupt. In the description of nature there are lines of lyrical beauty, but on the whole the writing style did not appeal to me. Too often it is theatrical, overdone and lacks clarity. As a specimen of nature writing, <u>there are just not enough lines of high caliber to counter the evasiveness characterizing her ability to express, or for that matter tackle, her emotional problems</u>. It seemed often she found it easier to discuss White than herself. <br /><br />How Macdonald eventually came to cope with her grief, as it is discussed in the book, come as flashes of insight rather than through thoughtful analysis. It took me a good two thirds of the book to be able to intuit why she thought training a hawk could help her handle her grief! At the book’s conclusion, I cannot help but wonder if it wasn’t merely the passage of time that lessened her grief. <a class="jsShowSpoiler spoilerAction">(view spoiler)</a><span class="spoilerContainer" style="display: none">[ Eventually, a doctor was involved, and he gave her antidepressants.  <a class="jsHideSpoiler spoilerAction">(hide spoiler)</a>]</span><br /><br />I wanted to feel sympathy for Macdonald. I wanted to feel attachment to Mabel. I felt neither. The “sport” repulses me. I personally do not see the joy of holding a “killing machine” in one’s hand, and the book did not convince me otherwise. I do perceive that there does develop a strong bond between falconer and raptor. <br /><br />The occasional lyrical lines describing nature, some interesting information on the history of falconry and books written on the subject allowed me to appreciate the book to some extent. Having recently read <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/1071726.The_Peregrine" title="The Peregrine by J.A. Baker" rel="nofollow noopener">The Peregrine</a> by <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/author/show/531605.J_A__Baker" title="J.A. Baker" rel="nofollow noopener">J.A. Baker</a>, one of the books mentioned, I appreciated getting another perspective on how that book was viewed when it first came out. <br /><br />The author narrates the audiobook, and she does a remarkably good job. Few authors are capable of such a good reading. I always understood what was said, and it is read with feeling.</span>
  <a data-text-id="9286997174884935367" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

